\begin{abstract}
Changes in the Earth's rate of rotation and the orientation of its rotational pole, i.e the Earth Rotation Parameters, are observed regularly.
At timescales shorter than a few years, fluctuations in these parameters are largely driven by changes in atmospheric angular momentum, which implies that these observations contain useful information about the dynamics of the atmosphere.
It has therefore been proposed to assimilate these parameters into atmosphere and ocean models, as an additional observable constraint for prediction and model evaluation/
In this study we test this idea by performing Observing System Simulation Experiments (OSSEs), using an Ensemble Adjustment Kalman Filter and the Community Atmosphere Model 5.
We show that the assimilation of atmospheric angular momentum, as observed via Earth rotation variations, is able to reduce large-scale error in the ensemble, even though the assimilated variables represent integrals of the atmospheric state.  
Error reduction is possible as long as the spread of the ensemble itself is relatively small, but this is a difficult condition to maintain if only global angular momentum functions are assimilated.
It is difficult to show that the assimilation of Earth rotation parameters / atmospheric angular momentum adds any value to the assimilation of more conventional, localized observations.
However, including atmospheric angular momentum in an assimilation experiment as evaluated variables only provides a useful measure for the fidelity of an assimilation system.  
The results found here could be extended to other cases where integral or averaged observations are assimilated.

\end{abstract}

