\subsection{Perfect-model experiments}
\label{sec:experiments}

We  perform so-called perfect-model experiments, wherein the ``truth'' is actually a model simulation, and observations are generated from this simulation with known error statistics, then assimilated back into the model.
Perfect model experiments are designed to show how much information can truly be recovered by assimilation in the absence of unknown model and obsersvation errors.
This is impossible to do with the assimilation of real observations, where the true state and the accuracies of the model and observation operators are not known.


\subsubsection{Ensemble Generation}
All assimilation runs were performed with an 80-member ensemble.
The ensemble is generated by selecting 80 random 1 January states from a long simulation of CAM5, and then running a year of assimilation of the radiosonde observations (Section \ref{sec:radiosondes}).


\subsubsection{Output Diagnostics}
Our main evaluation diagnostics are the square error between the simulated true state and the ensemble mean
\begin{eqnarray}
E_M = \left(
\left< x \right>-x_t
\right)^2
\end{eqnarray}
and the ensemble variance about its mean:
\begin{eqnarray}
S = 
\frac{1}{N}
\sum_{j=1}^N
\left(
\left< x_j \right>-x_t
\right)^2,
\end{eqnarray}
where $x$ represents the a component of the state vector in the ensemble,  $x_t$ a component of the true state, and $\left< \cdot \right>$ represents the ensemble mean.

To evaluate how much information is actually gained from assimilation in each case, we compare the the mean square error, $\llbracket E_M \rrbracket$ (where the brackets represent a spatial average) between the three assimilation experiments and the NoDA experiment.
To evaluate whether the ensemble is an accurate representation of the true uncertainty, we test whether the truth is indeed a sample of the probability distribution represented by the ensemble.
Here  we follow \citet{Huntley2009}, who used the theory of \citet{Murphy1988} that this is the case when 
\begin{eqnarray}
\llbracket E_M \rrbracket = \frac{N+1}{N} \llbracket S \rrbracket.
\label{eq:EvsS}
\end{eqnarray}

