In order for the assimilation experiments of the next section to be successful, they should achieve two goals: (1) to decrease the true error, and (2) to maintain an ensemble that comes from the same probability distribution of which the true state can also be considered a sample.

\subsubsection{Assimilation of AAM}

Figure \ref{fig:ERPDA_error_growth} compare the ensemble mean MSE and the scaled ensemble variance, as in Fig. \ref{fig:NODA}, but for the AAM experiment.  
Comparison between Figures \ref{fig:ERPDA_error_growth} and \ref{fig:NODA} shows that the assimilation of the three angular momentum functions slows down the initial growth of error and ensemble variance in both the wind and surface pressure.
However, the assimilation decreases the ensemble spread more strongly than the actual error.

This can be seen more clearly in Figure \ref{fig:ERPDA_diff}, which shows the MSE and variance of the AAM experiment minus that of the NODA experiment.
Here it is clear that while MSE in both variables is indeed reduced by the assimilation (negative values) sometimes, it is also increased be the assimilation at other times.
In contrast, the assimilation always decreases the ensemble variance
. 

In the global average (third column of Fig. \ref{fig:ERPDA_diff}), we see that the assimilation of the AAM functions is generally able to reduce the overall error in the wind fields for roughly the first 3 weeks of assimilation, but then begins to increase the true error.
In the surface pressure fields, the assimilation produces a global mean increase in the error starting as early as 10 days after the start of the experiment.

Figure \ref{fig:compare_divergence_basic} takes a closer look at the effect of AAM assimilation on the divergence of the ensemble filter, by comparing the difference between the MSE and the scaled variance with and without assimilation, again comparing the zonal wind and surface pressure.
For both variables, we can see that even when the difference between the true error and the ensemble variance is rather small, it is almost always larger when the three AAM components are assimilated. 
Divergence of the filter seems to be somewhat less severe for surface pressure, perhaps because it is a smaller field and thus slightly more easy to constrain with the three observations.

In summary, the assimilation of global AAM functions can lend some initial improvement to the estimated state, but ultimately leads to divergence of the ensemble filter.
This indicates that the covariance model, represented by the ensemble, is failing.  
In the following section, we investigate more closely why this happens, and how this result stems from the use of integral observations.



\subsection{Evolution of the  Covariance Field}

It was seen above that the ensemble filter is able to update the state more or less correctly at the beginning of the assimilation, actually makes the error between the ensemble mean and the true state worse later on in the assimilation period.
The degree to which each variable field is changed as the assimilation progresses depends on the covariances between local variables (in our case, winds or surface pressure) and the global AAM functions (\ref{eq:covariance}).
The covariance $c_{x_iy}$ is estimated for each state variable $x_i$ and each observation $y$ by the statistics of the model ensemble.  
A point in the model state can have a large covariance with the global AAM either if it has a large variance, or if it has a large correlation to the global AAM, or both.



\section{Can Earth rotation observations add value?}

The previous sections showed that the assimilation of AAM observations can reduce error in the modeled wind and pressure fields, as long as the ensemble spread has not reached its saturation level. 
Thus it makes sense to test whether the assimilation of AAM is more successful if the AAM functions are assimilated together with (more conventional) spatially localized observations to keep the ensemble spread from growing.

In terms of the AAM functions themselves [Fig. \ref{fig:fit_to_LOD}(d)] we saw that combining regularly-spaced observations with the AAM observations yielded an overal better-constrained state.
However, we found that the same is not true in terms of the model state variables. 
\textcolor{alert}{[Insert figure showing that adding AAM to local temperature observations increases the error while decreasing the spread.]}

Figure \ref{fig:compare_divergence_added_value} is similar to Fig. \ref{fig:compare_divergence_basic}, but now comparing experiment RST to experiment RST+AAM.
Again, we see that the consequence of adding AAM components as an assimilation variables is that the filter diverges, and here the effect is much stronger than in the basic experiment (Fig. \ref{fig:compare_divergence_basic}).
 

